With the advent of large scale imaging techniques and Cre-lines experimentalists have sought to link cortical circuits with their function in sensory processing. In particular genetic Parvalbumin (PV+) and Somatostatin (Sst+) markers have been essential in disentangling GABAergic interactions in the cortex. However, so far no framework exists to assess how the known properties of these interneuron subtypes contributes to their functional roles in development and sensory processing.
Based on the current literature several broad properties can be assigned to PV+ neurons:
• Fast, strong responses, driven by feedforward and
recurrent input, weakly feature selective, providing
perisomatic inhibition.
and Sst+ neurons:
• Slow, facilitating responses, recurrently driven,
stronger feature selectivity and dendritic inhibition.

Here we demonstrate that the fast, feedforward and linear responses of PV+ neurons make them suited to driving local decorrelation and drive map development, while the slower integration and feature selectivity of Sst neurons makes them suited to mediating contextual interactions and gating long-range input.

In order to assess which inhibitory response properties are important for robust and stable orientation map development, we simulate an extension of the GCAL developmental model with distinct excitatory and inhibitory populations and vary the linearity and hysteresis time constant of the inhibitory population. The metrics we will use to assess how map development is affected are map stability (the mean similarity to the final map), map quality (pinwheel density) and excitatory selectivity.
